<subSubSection id="4CB96530B165FFAC58FE9A96FD76FDF7" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="041C36BBB165FFAC58FE9A96FE83FE7C" blockId="8.[189,310,400,426]" box="[189,310,400,426]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading id="5F5481D7B165FFAC58FE9A96FE83FE7C" bold="true" box="[189,310,400,426]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="3">
<emphasis id="36D7EAA9B165FFAC58FE9A96FE83FE7C" bold="true" box="[189,310,400,426]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="041C36BBB165FFAC58FE9AB9FD76FDF7" blockId="8.[189,1400,447,545]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">This species is distinguished by the presence of two conspicuous wings on the dorsal sepal (vs calys without wings in all other species). It also has leaves that are rough to the touch with aciculate hairs (vs glabrous or softly hairy in all other species).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4CB96530B165FFAC58FE9941FE09FD65" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="041C36BBB165FFAC58FE9941FEF1FDB7" blockId="8.[189,324,583,609]" box="[189,324,583,609]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading id="5F5481D7B165FFAC58FE9941FEF1FDB7" bold="true" box="[189,324,583,609]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="3">
<emphasis id="36D7EAA9B165FFAC58FE9941FEF1FDB7" bold="true" box="[189,324,583,609]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="041C36BBB165FFAC58FE9970FE09FD65" blockId="8.[189,1399,630,691]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The epithet derives from the Latin ʻ 
<emphasis id="36D7EAA9B165FFAC5A239970FD14FD59" box="[608,673,630,655]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">asper</emphasis>
ʼ, ʻroughʼ, and ʻ 
<emphasis id="36D7EAA9B165FFAC5B189970FC13FD46" box="[859,934,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">folium</emphasis>
ʼ, ʻleafʼ, reflecting the rough texture the leaves of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
